<promed@promedmail.org>
[Unfortunately, eradication of infected sources of the virus is the only
practical way of attempting to manage this disease. Much of the information
on management of plum pox disease is derived from the European literature.
The virus is spread by many insect species, but principally _Brachycaudus
cardui_, _B. helichrysi_, _Myzus persicae_ , and _Phorodon humuli_. A
problem in the eradication of infected trees may be wild species of
_Prunus_ which can be infected as a consequence of aphid transmission of
the virus and thus become sources for additional spread. The relevance of
wild species to perpetuation of the virus in the Niagara region remains to
be determined.
Although nectarines, plums, almonds and peaches are not on the ProMED-Plant
list of 30 major crops, the disease is of such economic importance to
orchardists that it warrants publication.
Additional information on the disease is available at the following web
sites: <http://www.scisoc.org/feature/NewViruses/Top.html> and
<http://www.scisoc.org/feature/PlumPox/Top.html> -Mod. DH]
